<section class="section-about-container">
  <h1 class="title-apropos">ABOUT</h1>
  <div class="section-about-wrapper">
    <article class="light-article-about">
      <h2 class="h2-light-article">Les Tourterelles</h2>
      <p>
        Did you know? Turtledoves are amongst if not the first migratory birds! Migration is driven primarily by
        food availability. The turtle-dove migrates between its European breeding grounds and Africa's vast Sahel belt
      </p><br>
      <p>
       Flying mostly at night, it can reach speeds of 60 km/h and cover up to 700 km without stopping. The journey is dangerous, and the greatest threats come from humans.
      </p>
      <div class="dots-container">
        <span class="dots">•</span>
        <span class="dots">•</span>
        <span class="dots">•</span>
        <span class="dots">•</span>
        <span class="dots">•</span>
        <span class="dots">•</span>
      </div>
    </article>
    <article class="dark-article-about">
      <p>
        If you consider the story of those birds, you'd soon notice the similarities it holds with another species: human. Migrant have been known to travel to developped countries in search for a better job, security, or health.
      </p><br>
      <p>
        According to INSEE 49.5% of migrant living In france in 2019 are from Africa.  Probably due to France's history with these countries, mostly migrants travel from Morroco 9.4 %, Algeria 7 % and Tunisia.  Another point to note is that men were the ones migrating. In 2019 it was 51% of women migrating. Despite the raising number, it is harder for a woman to find her place in society compared to men.
      </p><br>
      <p>
        For this reason, the women at Les Tourterelles help them find their path not only with charity work they already provide but also through workshops destined to empower by gaining knowledge or simply to simply give a chance to connect with other women during events.
      </p>
    </article>
  </div>
</section>
